*** 2. We expect the carat of the diamonds to be strong correlated with the physical dimensions x, y and z. Use ggpairs() to investigate correlations between these four variables.

library(GGally)

carat_xyz <- diamonds %>%
  select(carat, x, y, z)

ggpairs(carat_xyz)

all corr above 0.9 so very high correlations

*** 3. So, we do find significant correlations. Lets drop columns x, y and z from the dataset, in preparation to use only carat going forward.

diamonds_no_xyz <- diamonds %>%
  select(-c(x, y, z))
diamonds_no_xyz

*** 4. We are interested in developing a regression model for the price of a diamond in terms of the possible predictor variables in the dataset.

*** i. Use ggpairs() to investigate correlations between price and the predictors (this may take a while to run, dont worry, make coffee or something).

ggpairs(diamonds_no_xyz)

*** ii. Perform further ggplot visualisations of any significant correlations you find.

diamonds_no_xyz %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

model <- lm(price ~ carat, data = diamonds_no_xyz)
model

Call:
lm(formula = price ~ carat, data = diamonds_no_xyz)

Coefficients:
(Intercept)        carat  
      -2256         7756  
library(ggfortify)
autoplot(model)

*** 5. Shortly we may try a regression fit using one or more of the categorical predictors cut, clarity and color, so lets investigate these predictors:

*** i. Investigate the factor levels of these predictors. How many dummy variables do you expect for each of them?

unique(diamonds_no_xyz$cut)
[1] "Ideal"     "Premium"   "Good"      "Very Good" "Fair"

cut <- 4 clarity <- 7 color <- 6

*** ii. Use the dummy_cols() function in the fastDummies package to generate dummies for these predictors and check the number of dummies in each case.

library(fastDummies)

dummy <- diamonds_no_xyz %>%
  dummy_cols(select_columns = "cut", remove_first_dummy = TRUE, remove_selected_columns = TRUE)

*** 6. Going forward well let R handle dummy variable creation for categorical predictors in regression fitting (remember lm() will generate the correct numbers of dummy levels automatically, absorbing one of the levels into the intercept as a reference level)

*** i. First, well start with simple linear regression. Regress price on carat and check the regression diagnostics.

*** ii. Run a regression with one or both of the predictor and response variables log() transformed and recheck the diagnostics. Do you see any improvement?

*** iii. Lets use log() transformations of both predictor and response. Next, experiment with adding a single categorical predictor into the model. Which categorical predictor is best? [Hint - investigate r2 values]
